  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most countries around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (such as funds from criminal activities like drug trafficking, corruption, or fraud) appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions that obscure the trail of the money.\n\nIn many jurisdictions, including China, money laundering is explicitly criminalized. In China, the crime of money laundering is stipulated in the \"Criminal Law of the People's Republic of China.\" According to Article 191 of the Criminal Law, individuals who convert illegal gains into seemingly legal property through various means, such as financial accounts, property transactions, or other methods, can be subject to severe penalties, including imprisonment, fines, or both.\n\nGovernments and international organizations actively combat money laundering to prevent the financial system from being exploited for criminal purposes and to promote transparency and accountability in financial transactions.",
